## 📘 TypeScript Fundamentals

TypeScript is a **statically-typed superset of JavaScript**. It adds a type system that catches bugs at development time (before you even run the code), making large codebases dramatically easier to maintain.

---

## 1️⃣ Why TypeScript?

```javascript
// JavaScript — no type safety
function multiply(a, b) { return a * b }
multiply("5", 2)  // Returns "52" (string concatenation!) — JavaScript silently wrong

// TypeScript — type error at compile time
function multiply(a: number, b: number): number { return a * b }
multiply("5", 2)  // ❌ Error: Argument of type 'string' is not assignable to 'number'
```

**Benefits:**
- Catch bugs before running code
- Better IDE autocompletion and IntelliSense
- Self-documenting code
- Safer refactoring

---

## 2️⃣ Basic Types

```typescript
// Primitives
let name: string = "Mwero"
let age: number = 28
let isAdmin: boolean = true
let nothing: null = null
let notSet: undefined = undefined

// Arrays
let scores: number[] = [95, 80, 72]
let names: Array<string> = ["Alice", "Bob"]

// Tuples (fixed-length, typed array)
let coordinate: [number, number] = [40.7, -74.0]

// Any (avoid — defeats TypeScript's purpose)
let data: any = "could be anything"

// Unknown (safer than any — must type-check before use)
let input: unknown = getInput()
if (typeof input === "string") { input.toUpperCase() }
```

---

## 3️⃣ Type Inference

TypeScript is smart enough to infer types from context — you don't need to annotate everything:

```typescript
const name = "Mwero"       // TypeScript infers: string
const scores = [1, 2, 3]   // TypeScript infers: number[]
const user = { name: "Mwero", age: 28 }  // Infers object shape

function add(a: number, b: number) {
  return a + b  // Return type inferred as number
}
```

---

## 4️⃣ Interfaces vs Types

Both define the shape of an object:

```typescript
// Interface — good for defining object shapes, extendable
interface User {
  id: number
  name: string
  email: string
  role?: "admin" | "user"  // Optional field (?)
  readonly createdAt: Date  // Cannot be changed after creation
}

// Type alias — more flexible, can define unions, primitives, tuples
type ID = string | number  // Union type
type Point = { x: number; y: number }
type Status = "pending" | "active" | "inactive"  // String literal union

// Extending interfaces
interface AdminUser extends User {
  permissions: string[]
}
```

**Rule of thumb:** Use `interface` for object shapes, `type` for unions and aliases.

---

## 5️⃣ Union & Intersection Types

```typescript
// Union type (either/or)
type Result = string | number | null
let value: Result = "hello"  // OK
value = 42                    // OK
value = false                 // ❌ Error

// Intersection type (combine both)
type A = { name: string }
type B = { age: number }
type AB = A & B  // { name: string; age: number }

const person: AB = { name: "Mwero", age: 28 }
```

---

## 6️⃣ Generics — Reusable, Typed Components

Generics allow types to be parameterized:

```typescript
// Generic function
function first<T>(arr: T[]): T | undefined {
  return arr[0]
}
first([1, 2, 3])       // Returns number
first(["a", "b"])      // Returns string

// Generic interface
interface ApiResponse<T> {
  data: T
  status: number
  message: string
}

const userResponse: ApiResponse<User> = {
  data: { id: 1, name: "Mwero", email: "m@m.com", createdAt: new Date() },
  status: 200,
  message: "OK"
}
```

---

## 7️⃣ Type Narrowing & Guards

```typescript
// typeof guard
function processInput(input: string | number) {
  if (typeof input === "string") {
    return input.toUpperCase()  // input is string here
  }
  return input.toFixed(2)       // input is number here
}

// instanceof guard
function processValue(value: Date | string) {
  if (value instanceof Date) {
    return value.toISOString()
  }
  return new Date(value).toISOString()
}

// Discriminated unions (pattern)
type Shape =
  | { kind: "circle"; radius: number }
  | { kind: "square"; side: number }

function area(shape: Shape): number {
  switch (shape.kind) {
    case "circle": return Math.PI * shape.radius ** 2
    case "square": return shape.side ** 2
  }
}
```

---

## 8️⃣ Utility Types

TypeScript's built-in generic utility types:

```typescript
interface User { id: number; name: string; email: string; password: string }

Partial<User>          // All fields optional
Required<User>         // All fields required
Readonly<User>         // All fields immutable
Pick<User, "id"|"name"> // Only these fields: { id: number; name: string }
Omit<User, "password"> // Exclude fields: { id, name, email }
Record<string, number> // { [key: string]: number }
Exclude<"a"|"b"|"c", "a"> // "b" | "c"
ReturnType<typeof myFn>   // Infer return type of a function
```

---

## 9️⃣ Enums

```typescript
// Numeric enum (auto-increments)
enum Direction { Up, Down, Left, Right }
// Direction.Up = 0, Down = 1, Left = 2, Right = 3

// String enum (more explicit, preferred)
enum Status {
  Pending = "PENDING",
  Active = "ACTIVE",
  Inactive = "INACTIVE"
}
const s: Status = Status.Active  // "ACTIVE"

// Const enums (erased at compile time — no runtime overhead)
const enum HttpMethod { GET = "GET", POST = "POST", DELETE = "DELETE" }
```

---

## 🔟 Non-Null Assertion & Type Casting

```typescript
// Non-null assertion (!) — tells TypeScript "I know this is not null"
const input = document.getElementById("myInput")!  // Override null possibility
input.focus()  // No error

// Type assertion (as) — override TypeScript's inference
const value = someFunction() as string
const canvas = document.getElementById("canvas") as HTMLCanvasElement
const canvas2 = <HTMLCanvasElement>document.getElementById("canvas") // JSX alternative

// Avoid both when possible — they bypass type safety
```

---

## 💡 Key Concepts

| Concept | Purpose |
|---|---|
| Static typing | Catch bugs at compile time |
| `interface` | Define object shapes |
| `type` | Unions, aliases, complex types |
| `?` | Optional property |
| `readonly` | Immutable property |
| Generics `<T>` | Reusable typed patterns |
| Union `A | B` | Either type |
| Intersection `A & B` | Both types |
| Utility types | Transform existing types |
| Type narrowing | Narrow union to specific type |
